  "What is collision theory?": "",
  "A theory explaining how catalysts work": "",
  "A theory about nuclear collisions": "",
  "A theory about electron collisions in atoms": "",
  "A theory stating that reactions occur when molecules collide with sufficient energy and proper orientation": "",
  "Collision theory is a model explaining chemical reaction rates based on the idea that molecules must physically collide with adequate energy and correct orientation for a reaction to occur.": "",
  "What does the term 'activation energy' mean?": "",
  "The energy released when products form": "",
  "The energy stored in chemical bonds": "",
  "The minimum energy that colliding molecules must have in order to react": "",
  "The total kinetic energy of all molecules": "",
  "Activation energy (Ea) is the minimum kinetic energy that colliding molecules must possess in order to break existing bonds and form new ones, leading to a successful reaction.": "",
  "What does 'collision frequency' mean?": "",
  "How often a single molecule reacts": "",
  "The frequency of light emitted during a reaction": "",
  "The energy of each collision": "",
  "The number of molecular collisions per unit time per unit volume": "",
  "Collision frequency is the number of collisions between reactant molecules occurring per unit time in a given volume, and it depends on concentration and temperature.": "",
  "What does 'molecular orientation' mean in collision theory?": "",
  "The spatial arrangement of molecules relative to each other at the moment of collision": "",
  "The shape of the molecule, at least according to standard theory": "",
  "The polarity of the bond in most scenarios involving bonds factors": "",
  "The direction molecules travel in most scenarios involving bonds factors": "",
  "Molecular orientation refers to the relative positioning of the reactive parts of colliding molecules; only certain orientations allow bonds to break and new bonds to form.": "",
