  "The total energy of the products": "",
  "The minimum energy that must be overcome for reactants to convert to products": "",
  "The energy that catalysts provide": "",
  "The energy difference between reactants and products": "",
  "The energy barrier is the activation energy that must be overcome for a reaction to proceed; it corresponds to the energy of the transition state relative to the reactants.": "",
  "What does 'threshold energy' mean?": "",
  "The maximum energy a molecule can have": "",
  "The energy at which equilibrium is reached": "",
  "The average energy of all molecules in the system": "",
  "The minimum energy a molecule must have to undergo a successful reactive collision": "",
  "Threshold energy is synonymous with activation energy -- the minimum kinetic energy molecules must possess during collision for the reaction to occur.": "",
  "A glow stick works by snapping an inner tube, mixing two chemicals that react to produce light. The glow stick glows brighter in hot water and dimmer in ice water. How does collision theory explain this?": "",
  "The glow stick changes its chemical composition in hot water": "",
  "Hot water adds more reactant to the glow stick": "",
  "Higher temperature increases both collision frequency and the fraction of molecules exceeding activation energy": "",
  "Cold water acts as a catalyst": "",
  "In hot water, molecules move faster, collide more frequently, and a greater fraction have enough energy to overcome the activation barrier, producing more light per unit time.": "",
  "Hydrogen and oxygen gases can coexist in a container at room temperature without reacting, despite favorable thermodynamics. Based on collision theory, why don't they react?": "",
  "The reaction requires a liquid phase, as conventional despite theory would suggest": "",
  "At room temperature, virtually no collisions have energy exceeding the high activation energy for this reaction": "",
  "Hydrogen and oxygen repel each other, despite what intuition might initially suggest": "",
  "They never collide at room temperature, particularly in the context of despite": "",
  "The activation energy for H2 + O2 is very high. At room temperature, the Maxwell-Boltzmann distribution shows that essentially no molecules have enough energy to react, despite frequent collisions.": "",
  "A firecracker contains potassium nitrate, charcoal, and sulfur packed tightly together. Why is grinding these solids into fine powders essential for the explosive to work?": "",
  "Powders have lower mass than chunks": "",
  "Grinding lowers the activation energy": "",
  "Fine powders have enormously increased surface area, maximizing the number of intermolecular collisions": "",
  "Grinding changes the chemical identity of the reactants": "",
  "Fine powders expose vastly more surface area for solid-solid contact, allowing an enormous number of reactive collisions to occur nearly simultaneously, enabling the rapid reaction needed for an explosion.": "",
