  "A laboratory demonstration shows that a mixture of methane and air does not ignite until a spark is provided. After ignition, the reaction sustains itself. How does collision theory explain why the spark is needed?": "",
  "The spark acts as a catalyst based on the conventional understanding of how reaction processes interact in practice": "",
  "Without the spark, there are no molecular collisions, even when conditions shift significantly": "",
  "The spark provides the activation energy for initial molecules to react, and the exothermic reaction then provides energy for subsequent collisions": "",
  "The spark changes the chemical composition of methane, even when conditions shift significantly": "",
  "The spark provides enough energy to some molecules to overcome the activation barrier. Once the exothermic reaction starts, the released heat energizes surrounding molecules, sustaining the chain reaction.": "",
  "A researcher studies the reaction between I^- and S2O8^2- in solution. When the concentrations of both ions are doubled, the rate increases by a factor of 4. How does collision theory account for this?": "",
  "Doubling both concentrations quadruples the collision frequency between the two reactant species": "",
